article.description: Area native Jason Terry had 32 points but the Seattle SuperSonics edged the Atlanta Hawks, 99-96.
article.headline: Sonics continue to cook without injured Baker
article.linkText: Sonics hold off Hawks for fourth win in five games
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- The Seattle SuperSonics are finding they can win without Vin Baker.
Payton

Gary Payton and Jerome James had baskets and Desmond Mason hit two free throws in the final minute as the Sonics beat the Atlanta Hawks 99-96 on Friday night. The Sonics won for the fourth time in five games since losing Baker, their starting power forward, with three dislocated toes on his left foot. The team put Baker, whose left foot is in a protective boot, on the injured list Friday. He will not accompany the team on its upcoming five-game road trip. "We've been having a lot more success moving the ball," the Sonics' Brent Barry said. Mason was fouled deliberately by Dion Glover and made his free throws with 12.2 seconds left after Atlanta's Jason Terry made a 3-point shot with 13.1 seconds left. Shareef Abdur-Rahim of the Hawks missed a 3-point attempt over Payton in the final seconds. Payton led Seattle with 21 points and eight assists, while Barry and Mason each finished with 17 points. For Atlanta, Terry scored 32 points on 12-for-25 shooting and had eight assists, while Abdur-Rahim had 25 points and 16 rebounds. "I think we finally realized that we were without Vin Baker," Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "I think the first couple of games we were playing on emotions and everybody was excited and pumped. Then all of a sudden, we realized this guy's not here." The Sonics didn't play exceptionally well, but they played well enough to win. "A win is a win," Payton said. "I'm not worried about how we did it." The Hawks lost their third straight road game and dropped to 7-24 on the road this season. "That was tough," said Terry, who is from Seattle and who had 65 friends and family members in the crowd. "But the Sonics stayed resilient and showed why they're a good team in the West. And G.P. did what he had to do down the stretch by finding the right people." Barry scored all his points in the second half, making four of five 3-point attempts. Barry, who scored 11 points in the third quarter, hit a 3-pointer and James grabbed a rebound on a missed 3-pointer by Mason and dunked it to tie the score at 88 with 4:51 to go. Rashard Lewis of Seattle hit a 3-pointer after a pass from Payton with 4:03 on the clock and Payton hit a scoop shot with 3:28 to go to put the Sonics in front 93-88. But Abdur-Rahim's layup and two free throws by Alan Henderson with 2:25 to go cut Seattle's lead to 93-92. Payton answered with a seven-footer with 59 seconds left before Abdur-Rahim hit a free throw with 40.6 seconds left to make the score 95-93 for Seattle. Payton missed a five-footer, but James, a 7-foot-1, 270-pounder who signed with the Sonics as a free agent before the season, grabbed the offensive rebound and scored on a putback with 26.9 seconds remaining. James didn't think he did anything special. "My whole thing was to get back and play defense," he said with a smile. "I didn't even think about it. I was just thinking about playing defense." Baker's absence has meant more playing time for James, who had nine points, seven rebounds and a blocked shot in 22 minutes. "I'm just happy to see that he's out there doing things for this team that sacrifice some of his game," Barry said. "We don't give him the ball a lot on the postup, we ask him to defend, come over and help, block shots, set pick and rolls for Gary and he's willing to do that. When you have teammates who play that way, it lends to success for everybody." The Sonics improved their record to 14-8 against Eastern Conference teams. It was their first game of the season against the Hawks. In games without Baker, they're 11-4 this season.

Game notes
The Sonics don't know when they're going to get Baker back. Baker, injured against the Los Angeles Lakers on Feb. 14, is averaging 16.6 points and 6.8 rebounds. The Sonics did not add a player to their roster to replace Baker, leaving them with 11 players. ... F Toni Kukoc of the Hawks missed his 23rd game of the season after being hit on the right wrist in Portland Thursday night. Kukoc, 33, was activated off the injured list last Sunday. He was placed on the injured list Jan. 10 with a fractured right wrist.
